  "photo": "https://image.tmdb.org/t/p/h632/faKr66V0EzJVMXwr0kIlSr9vfp7.jpg",
  "blurb": "The defining American comic of the 2010s: observational, autobiographical, dark about mortality and shame, and the first comedian to prove a stand-up could sell his own work direct.",
  "bio": "Louis Székely, born September 12, 1967, in Washington D.C., was raised in Mexico City until age seven, when his family moved to Massachusetts. He began stand-up at a Boston open mic in 1985, moved to New York in 1989, and built a writing career through the 1990s on Late Night with Conan O'Brien, The Dana Carvey Show, The Chris Rock Show, and Saturday Night Live. He directed Tomorrow Night (1998) and Pootie Tang (2001), then broke through as a stand-up with Shameless (2007), Chewed Up (2008), and Hilarious (2010). In 2011 he pioneered the direct-to-fan model by self-releasing Live at the Beacon Theater for $5 on his website. His FX series Louie (2010–2015) won multiple Emmys; he won three Grammys for Best Comedy Album (Hilarious 2012, Live at Madison Square Garden 2016, Sincerely Louis C.K. 2022). In November 2017, after New York Times reporting, he admitted to sexual misconduct involving five women; he stepped away from public life for roughly a year before returning to touring and self-distributing further specials.",
